Storm update. Our trail team has been out assessing blocked trails and we’re looking at almost 100 downed trees blocking trails. Our staff is currently focusing on clearing our paved River Parks trails for use and once debris is pushed to side there, we will have them up to turkey to work on the the dirt trails. Our priorities will be the shared trails that serve as main arteries on the Mtn. They will then have to return to the River Park to remove debris. We are organizing our trail team volunteers to help clean up what they can when they can in addition to staff working. This process is projected to take a few weeks to get the main trails cleared. Be aware, if you visit turkey you will likely not get far before downed trees block paths.

Turkey Trail Update for Thursday. Huge thanks to all the Turkey Trail Team, Volunteers, RPA staff, @tulsauwc and more for all their help this week. 100 hours the storm and trails are mostly cleared.  Over 120 blockages removed in less than 100 hours. Incredible!

If you answered yes, please consider the following best practices:
Tip #1 – Avoid using noise-canceling headphones.
Tip #2 – Utilize the Awareness! Often headphones prohibit you from hearing other trail users behind you from asking to pass.
Tip #3 – Run one earbud in and one out.
Tip #4 – Consider wearing on ear workout headphones and not ones that completely cover your ears
Tip #5 – Keep your volume down.
We recognize that some enjoy cranking up the tunes when enjoying the trails but please note that it can be unsafe when you can't hear what's going on around you. We also realize this post will be controversial for some and ask to please be kind.

What do the “color” of the trails mean? 
🟢 - Easy for hiking or beginner Mtn bikers
🟦 - moderately difficult for hiking or intermediate skills required for Mtn bikers
⬛️ - difficult for hikers and expert skill required for mtb

Take extra precautions if you spend time outside. When
possible, reschedule strenuous activities to early morning or
evening. Know the signs and symptoms of heat exhaustion and heat stroke. Wear light weight and loose fitting clothing and drink plenty of water. At minimum in this heat should be 12 oz every 30minutes. More if running or biking.

Under Title 26, Section 105 of the Tulsa Code Of Ordinances it is unlawful to have any animal in a park or natural area unless the animal is on a leash not exceeding six (6) feet in length. And please remove pet waste COMPLETELY from the park. Leaving it on the side of the trail for someone else to pick up doesn't count!

The temperatures are becoming dangerously hot, especially for dogs. Please bring just as much water for your pets as you would yourselves in these temperatures. Avoid coming in the heat of the day and familiarize yourself with the symptoms of heat exhaustion and heat stroke.

River Parks’ signature fall fundraiser, Wild Turkey, returns on Thursday, September 28, 2023.  As autumn colors emerge among the forested hills of Turkey Mountain, a casual evening under the stars beckons!  Unwind in your most comfortable outdoor wear, visiting with friends old and new, sharing BBQ and bonfires as the sun dips below the horizon.  Entertainment features bluegrass, short moonlight strolls at the trailhead, and birds from the Sutton Avian Research Center.
 
Wild Turkey benefits the Turkey Mountain Urban Wilderness, Tulsa’s treasure trove of winding trails, quiet ponds and meadows, valleys and vistas.  Each year, tens of thousands hike, bike and ramble the wooded landscape, finding an uncommon respite in the heart of the city.  The 2020 Turkey Mountain Master Plan is guiding the park’s management to assure its viability for generations to come.  Your support of Wild Turkey is implementing the Master Plan’s goals:  preservation, restoration and recreation.
 
Progress toward these goals is evident through accomplishments to date:
• 16+ miles of trail have been rehabilitated to mitigate erosion and improve accessibility
•  the first controlled burn was conducted to begin thinning the understory and reduce wildfire danger
•  areas of invasive species are being removed to allow desirable vegetation to flourish
•  installation of new wayfinding signage has begun

River Parks Authority officials announced today a $2 million grant from the Darryl & Julie Christner Family Foundation (DJCFF) to further improve outdoor recreational opportunities at the Turkey Mountain Urban Wilderness, ultimately adding over 80 acres to the park’s current footprint.
Through this new partnership with DJCFF, River Parks will further its goal of providing more sustainably built trails to help disperse users and lessen negative impacts to the park by opening new areas.

 The new DJCFF funding will further expand trails into the Phase 5 area (see below map) located on property that has not traditionally been considered part of the core 650 acres of Turkey Mountain. Nearly 88 acres located south of 61st Street and west of Elwood on Turkey property are currently separated from the core of the park by a two-lane road. River Parks plans to install a crossing from the core area to the project area and develop 7-8 additional miles of trail for hikers and cyclists. This area will be opened to the public upon completion of safe crossings at 61st and Elwood. As a result, Turkey Mountain will have almost 750 acres of greenspace for Tulsans to enjoy.
“I believe that the recent transformations at Turkey Mountain have been absolutely amazing,” says Josh Christner, Executive Director of the Darryl & Julie Christner Family Foundation. “Our foundation is extremely honored to have the opportunity to contribute to the development of new recreation trails in Tulsa. Our foundation's primary mission is to enrich the community by promoting and improving the physical, emotional, and mental wellbeing of all individuals, as well as to leave a positive, lasting impact on generations to come. We believe this donation will not only embody this mission, but also allow both local residents as well as out-of-town visitors to enjoy even more of what Turkey Mountain has to offer.”
DJCFF’s funding contributions will be awarded incrementally over the next two years. Work is slated to begin in the spring of 2024 with completion by the end of that year.

**Attention Photographers at Turkey Mountain** 

Turkey is a great place for photography sessions. We do appreciate that you think our park is beautiful enough to serve as a backdrop for precious memories and we kindly remind everyone that the park is a public space shared by all visitors.

Please be mindful of others enjoying the park. Ensure that your photography sessions do not obstruct pathways, natural habitats, or the general public's enjoyment of the park. It's all about respecting the space and those around you!

📷 **A few friendly tips for photographers:**
- Plan your shoots to avoid busy times.
- Please don't trample plants and other vegetation. Stick to the trails.
- Keep equipment to a minimum to reduce space usage.
- Always give way to regular park visitors.
- Respect the natural environment – leave no trace.

Thank you for your understanding and cooperation! 🌳💚

Weather permitting, Bring in the new year right and head to Turkey Mountain for a First Day Guided Hike!  Free Guided Tours will be led every hour starting on the hour from 10am to 2pm thanks to volunteers from our Turkey Trail Team!

Those wishing to join the hike should meet at the main, lower, paved parking lot at 6850 S. Elwood Ave by the Turkey Welcome Sign, Big Horn Sheep Statue, and Restrooms. Tours will be approximately 2.2 miles and be moderate to moderately difficult. Very small children and those with mobility issues are encouraged to use our Faimly Gravel Trail “Tvlsi” or the paved trail instead of this moderately strenuous hike. Hikes will take about 1.5 hours. Sturdy shoes, weather appropriate clothing, and a water bottle highly encouraged. 

Tours will be led every hour starting on the hour from 10am to 2pm. 

10 am - Hike Leader - Bill
11 am - Hike Leader - Jeff
12 pm - Hike Leader - Bronwyn
  1 pm - Hike Leader - Shannon
  2 pm - Hike Leader - Ryan

First Day Hikes are part of a nationwide initiative led by America’s Parks to encourage people to get outdoors. Kids and adults all across America will be participating in First Day Hikes, getting their hearts pumping and enjoying the beauty of a Turkey Mountain. 

People are invited to savor the beauty of the park’s natural resources so they may be inspired to take advantage of these local treasures throughout the year.
